As shown in Fig. 3, the QY of N-CDs shows a first increase and subsequent decrease with increase of reaction temperature, which is consistent with the previously reported result [26]. The formation of CDs usually undergoes polymerization, crosslinking and carbonization processes [27]. Reaction temperature plays a crucial role in the formation of N-CDs. Also, the degree of carbonization could be visualized intuitively by the color of the resulting solution. So photographs of the resulting samples under daylight (Fig. 4
                           a), the dilute sample solution under daylight (Fig. 4b) and UV light (Fig. 4c, λex = 365 nm) were obtained. Furthermore, HRTEM images (Fig. 5
                           ), size distribution histograms (Fig. 6
                           ), FT-IR spectra (Fig. 7
                           ) and EA (Table 3
                           ) of all N-CDs have been presented in order to get better insight into the relation between the formation process of N-CDs and high QY. It is found that the color of solution (Fig. 4a) deepens and the content of hydroxy (Fig. 7a–c) and oxygen (Table 3) decreases gradually with the increase of temperature under a certain EDA dosage, indicating the aggravation of dehydration-carbonization process. At low temperature (150 °C), polymer-like CDs are generated owing to the insufficient carbonization degree (Figs. 5a–c and 6a–c). In this situation, the PL largely comes from the surface state (small amount of fluorophore connected on the polymer-like CDs), and the QY is relatively low (∼22%). With the increase of temperature (180 °C), hydroxyl content in N-CDs-6 (Fig. 7a), N-CDs-4 (Fig. 7b) and N-CDs-5 (Fig. 7c) decreases compared with that in N-CDs-1 (Fig. 7a), N-CDs-2 (Fig. 7b) and N-CDs-3 (Fig. 7c). Consequently, carbogenic CDs are produced owing to sufficient carbonization (Figs. 5d–f and 6d–f). In the meantime, the PL results from the synergistic effect of the carbogenic core and fluorophore, and the QY increases markedly (∼72%). However, as the carbonization process continues to strengthen at higher temperature (210 °C), the hydroxyl content is further lowered (Fig. 7a–c), during which the carbogenic core grows up constantly (Figs. 5g–i and 6g–i). Herein, PL mainly comes from the carbogenic core and the QY decreases slightly (∼70%).

In the XRD pattern of highly luminescent N-CDs (Fig. 8
                           ), the broad diffraction peak centered at 20° further reflects the existence of amorphous structure [30]. Besides, SAED pattern (inset of Fig. 8) reveals the highly luminescent N-CDs have no distinct diffraction ring, indicating its poor crystallinity. Also, surface chemical compositions and functional groups were detected by EA, XPS and FT-IR techniques, as presented in Table 3 and Fig. 9
                           . The highly luminescent N-CDs are composed of C 38.64 wt%, H 5.087 wt%, N 5.88 wt%, and O (calculated) 50.393 wt%. Accordingly, the atomic ratio of C, H, N, O is 1:1.580:0.130:0.978. The XPS full scan spectrum of highly luminescent N-CDs (Fig. 9a) reveals three peaks: C1s (284 eV), N1s (399 eV) and O1s (531 eV), indicating that the sample consists essentially of carbon, nitrogen and oxygen elements. Fig. 9b exhibits three main peaks at 284.21, 284.83 and 285.55 eV, which are related to C-C/C=C, C-O/C-N and C=O, respectively [16,17]. High resolution N1s spectrum presented in Fig. 9c shows that nitrogen atom exists in three chemical environments, corresponding to pyridinic N at 398.45 eV, pyrrolic N at 399.07 eV, and N-H at 400.52 eV [22,31]. To illustrate the chemical structure change during microwave-assisted reaction process, FT-IR spectra of reactant and resulting highly luminescent N-CDs were recorded as mentioned in Fig. 9d. CA mainly has oxygen-containing functional groups, including O-H (3371 and 3231 cm−1), C=O (1728 cm−1) and C-O (1213 and 1112 cm−1), as well as C-H (3036 cm−1) [31]. As for highly luminescent N-CDs, the characteristic absorption bands at 3435, 1708 and 1415 cm−1 are assigned to the stretching vibrations of O-H/N-H, C=O and C-N, indicating the formation of amide linkage during the reaction process [32]. Additionally, the sample also possesses abundant functional groups such as C-H (2947 and 1342 cm−1), C=N (1629 cm−1), C=C (1550 cm−1), C-O (1180 cm−1) and C-C-N (1223 cm−1) [33]. Above FT-IR results demonstrate the introduction of abundant oxygen- and nitrogen-containing functional groups onto the surface of highly luminescent N-CDs by dehydration, polymerization and carbonization process, which is consistent with XPS characterization.

UV–vis absorption, PLE and PL measurements were investigated to throw light on the luminescence properties of highly luminescent N-CDs. UV–vis absorption spectrum presented in Fig. 10
                           a exhibits two absorption peaks at 245 and 350 nm, the former is ascribed to the π–π* transition of C=C bond, while the latter to the n–π* transition of C=O bond [9]. First of all, the existence of C=C and C=O has been confirmed by XPS and FT-IR measurements. The π–π* transition suggests the presence of π-electron system, which is produced by the dehydration-carbonization process. The π-electron system can be forcefully combined with surface electronic states created by surface oxidation, consequently altering the whole electronic structure of the CDs to improve their QY and blue-to-red spectral composition [34,35]. The PLE spectrum of highly luminescent N-CDs (Fig. 10a) presents two peaks at 247 and 352 nm, which are very close to their UV–vis absorption peaks. PL spectra of highly luminescent N-CDs take on an excitation-independent behavior, as illustrated in Fig. 10b, which means that highly luminescent N-CDs have a relatively uniform size and surface state [22,25]. To be specific, surface state, involving surface traps in the radiative transition, plays a crucial role in the PL spectra (excitation-dependent or -independent) [29,36]. Different surface functional groups, including C-OH, C=O and COOH, could induce the formation of trapping states with different energy levels [37]. The character of luminescence depends on whether trapping states are passivated or not [29]. If the surface states are less passivated, one of the multiple surface states with a sequence of particular energies will occupy the primary role in the PL spectra depending on excitation energy. Under the circumstances, unpassivated N-CDs will exhibit excitation-dependent trait (left in Fig. 11
                           ). Alternatively, if every surface state is fully passivated, the emission will occur only through a specific radiative transition process, thus leading to excitation-independent feature (right in Fig. 11). In the current study, highly luminescent N-CDs are fully passivated by EDA, which is an effective passivating agent [18,38], thus leading to the excitation-independent behavior owing to the single transition mode with a certain energy. Besides, the EDA-free controlled trial (N-free-CDs) has been synthesized only using CA under the same experiment condition as highly luminescent N-CDs (180 °C, 8 min). The resulting solution is colorless and exhibits no fluorescence under a 365 nm UV lamp (inset at the left of Fig. 10b). However, the dilute aqueous solution of highly luminescent N-CDs (inset at the right of Fig. 10b) emits bright blue color under a hand-held UV lamp (λex = 365 nm), indicating EDA plays a crucial role in the formation of carbon dots and the generation of fluorescence. Meanwhile, the strong blue fluorescence intensity of highly luminescent N-CDs is consistent with the optimal emission peak at 442 nm under 360 nm excitation in the PL spectra, consequently, the highly luminescent N-CDs can serve as phosphor for white LEDs based on UV-LED chip.
